Bankruptcy is a very powerful part of US law. When a company files for bank=
ruptcy, it=E2=80=99s usually because a lot of people have a lot of valid cl=
aims against it. It has borrowed a lot of money, promised to pay it back, a=
nd failed to do so; perhaps it has taken money from customers and not deliv=
ered the goods; perhaps it has promised its workers pensions and reneged on=
 its promises; perhaps it has harmed a lot of people and been sued for dama=
ges.
All of those people have a good moral case to get their money, and also the=
y are=C2=A0legally=C2=A0entitled to it. But there is not enough money. And =
so the company files for bankruptcy, and the bankruptcy court has the power=
 to say =E2=80=9Cnope, you don=E2=80=99t get the money that you deserve and=
 are legally owed.=E2=80=9D There are specific rules in the bankruptcy code=
 that determine how the court uses that power =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally, sec=
ured creditors get paid back before unsecured ones, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 there is also an element of negotiation and compromise among the claimants=
, and an element of discretion for the bankruptcy judge. The bankruptcy jud=
ge=E2=80=99s basic role is to make the fairest possible division of what=E2=
=80=99s left in a fundamentally unfair situation.=C2=A0
And the judge has a lot of=C2=A0power=C2=A0to do that. If the company has, =
for instance, killed your relatives, and you have sued the company in your =
state=E2=80=99s courts to try to punish it and get compensation, the bankru=
ptcy judge can=C2=A0stop that lawsuit, because once the company is in bankr=
uptcy essentially all of the claims against it get centralized in bankruptc=
y. The bankruptcy court decides how to allocate the company=E2=80=99s asset=
s among the claimants, and then all of their claims are extinguished foreve=
r.=C2=A0
This power is so broad that bankruptcy judges sometimes go overboard.=C2=A0
We have talked a few times about the Purdue Pharma LP bankruptcy. The essen=
tial points are:
=09Purdue makes opioid painkillers that led to an addiction crisis and kill=
ed a lot of people.=09Various people =E2=80=94=C2=A0victims, their families=
, states, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0sued Purdue for its actions.=09This has left =
Purdue facing perhaps trillions of dollars of morally and legally valid obl=
igations to its victims.=09Purdue does not have trillions of dollars. Its b=
usiness is worth perhaps a few billion dollars.=09It filed for bankruptcy, =
and its lawyers, together with lawyers for victims and the bankruptcy court=
, came up with a plan to split up the value of Purdue and give it to the vi=
ctims.
  [1]
=C2=A0The victims would not get nearly as much as they would otherwise be e=
ntitled to =E2=80=94=C2=A0individual victims would get between $3,500 and $=
48,000 of compensation, orders of magnitude less than a jury would probably=
 give them =E2=80=94 but there is only so much money at Purdue.=09Purdue=E2=
=80=99s owners, the Sackler family, got very rich over the years from their=
 ownership of Purdue. In particular, in the years=C2=A0after=C2=A0the opioi=
d crisis became widely recognized, Purdue paid about $11 billion of dividen=
ds and distributions to the Sacklers. They are billionaires, even though th=
e company that they ran has a net worth of, on some assumptions,=C2=A0negat=
ive trillions of dollars.
=09This seems pretty unfair to, essentially, everybody. I mean even to the =
Sacklers, kind of.=09So the Sacklers offered to pitch in up to $6 billion o=
f their own money, as part of the bankruptcy plan,=C2=A0to help pay the opi=
oid victims.
  [2]

=09In exchange, though, they wanted the bankruptcy court to forever extingu=
ish all opioid-related lawsuits=C2=A0against them.=09The bankruptcy court =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and a majority, though not all, of the victims =E2=80=94 agr=
eed to the deal.

You can analyze that deal on several levels. There is the level of moral fa=
irness: The Sacklers, loosely speaking, extracted $11 billion for themselve=
s by running a company with a net social value of perhaps negative trillion=
s of dollars. And now they have agreed to give back roughly half of it, lea=
ving them still billionaires. Arguably you should become a billionaire by d=
oing stuff with=C2=A0positive=C2=A0value and keeping some of it for yoursel=
f; doing stuff with enormous=C2=A0negative value=C2=A0and getting billions =
for yourself seems bad. As a matter of fairness, the Sacklers should perhap=
s have to give back, you know, all of it, or almost all of it, or perhaps m=
ore than all of it.
But then there is the pragmatic level.=C2=A0How=C2=A0are you going to get t=
he Sacklers to give up all their money? You could sue them, sure, of course=
. The entity that is most obvious liable for the opioid crisis is=C2=A0Purd=
ue, the company, which is very bankrupt, but you can probably find some cau=
ses of action to sue the Sacklers. For one thing, some Sacklers were execut=
ives or board members of Purdue, so you could sue them personally for their=
 own actions running Purdue. (But not all of them were.) For another thing,=
 there are arguments under the bankruptcy code that they should not have be=
en able to extract $11 billion from the company while it was facing all thi=
s opioid liability, that the dividends they got were =E2=80=9Cfraudulent tr=
ansfers=E2=80=9D and can be clawed back by the company.
There are problems with all of this. There are a lot of Sacklers. They can =
hire good lawyers. Some of them live abroad. Much of their money is in trus=
ts that a US court might not be able to get access to. If you sued all of t=
hem, it would be expensive and time-consuming and you might not get much mo=
ney. You might! And you might at least make life very unpleasant for them, =
which has its own virtues.
But the majority of the victims, and the bankruptcy court, concluded that g=
etting $6 billion from the Sacklers in the bankruptcy settlement was better=
 than the victims would do by suing them personally. And so they reached th=
e pragmatic compromise that they=E2=80=99d take $6 billion, and=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0sue for the rest, rather than trying to get the whole $11 billion and po=
ssibly ending up with nothing.
But then there is the legal level. The Sacklers weren=E2=80=99t willing to =
pay $6 billion just to get=C2=A0most, or=C2=A0almost all, of the victims to=
 agree not to sue them. There are so many victims, so many people who could=
 sue. If they paid the $6 billion to extinguish 99% of the claims, they wou=
ld still spend the rest of their lives fighting lawsuits from the other 1% =
of the victims.
The Sacklers wanted to pay $6 billion to get rid of=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the cl=
aims against them
  [3]
:
The Sackler discharge they proposed comprised a release and an injunction. =
The release sought to void not just current opioid-related claims against t=
he family, but future ones as well. It sought to ban not just claims by cre=
ditors participating in the bankruptcy proceeding, but claims by anyone who=
 might otherwise sue Purdue. It sought to extinguish not only claims for ne=
gligence, but also claims for fraud and willful misconduct. And it proposed=
 to end all these lawsuits without the consent of the opioid victims who br=
ought them. To enforce this release, the Sacklers sought an injunction =E2=
=80=9Cforever stay[ing], restrain[ing,] and enjoin[ing]=E2=80=9D claims aga=
inst them. That injunction would not just prevent suits against the company=
=E2=80=99s officers and directors but would run in favor of hundreds, if no=
t thousands, of Sackler family members and entities under their control.=E2=
=80=9D
They wanted the bankruptcy court to issue an order saying, in essence, that=
 nobody could sue the Sacklers over opioids ever again.
This, again, is a thing that bankruptcy courts do! Almost. Bankruptcy court=
s=C2=A0are, at their core, in the business of issuing orders saying that no=
body can sue the bankrupt company ever again. That's what they do; that=E2=
=80=99s what bankruptcy is. But of course=C2=A0the Sacklers aren=E2=80=99t =
bankrupt. The bankruptcy case is about Purdue, the company, not the Sackler=
s personally. It=E2=80=99s just that, to fairly resolve the Purdue bankrupt=
cy =E2=80=94=C2=A0to maximize the amount of money Purdue has to distribute =
to victims, and to distribute it fairly =E2=80=94=C2=A0it would help to get=
 the $6 billion from the Sacklers, and in exchange for that $6 billion they=
 want the same finality that Purdue gets.
This is, in bankruptcy law, called a =E2=80=9Cthird-party release=E2=80=9D:=
 The idea is that the bankruptcy court extinguishes all the claims, not onl=
y against the bankrupt company, but also against some related third parties=
 who are involved with the company. Some bankruptcy courts think that this =
is allowed, part of the enormous power they have to craft fair outcomes and=
 reasonable compromises. Other bankruptcy courts think that it is not allow=
ed: The bankruptcy code gives them the power to end all lawsuits against=C2=
=A0the bankrupt company, but that=E2=80=99s it. Stopping people who are not=
 in bankruptcy from suing other people who are not in bankruptcy is a clear=
 overreach.
My impression is that, as a pragmatic matter, giving the Sacklers a third-p=
arty release was probably a good idea, but that, as a legal matter, it does=
 seem pretty iffy.=C2=A0
Anyway, the bankruptcy court gave them the release. A federal district cour=
t reversed, saying that third-party releases are illegal. Last year, an app=
eals court reversed again, allowing the third-party release. And today, on =
a 5-to-4 vote, the US Supreme Court reversed again, finding that third-part=
y releases are not allowed. Justice Neil Gorsuch wrote the majority opinion=
, emphasizing the unfairness of granting the release:
But beneath [the bankruptcy code=E2=80=99s] complexity lies a simple bargai=
n: A debtor can win a discharge of its debts if it proceeds with honesty an=
d places virtually all its assets on the table for its creditors. The debto=
r in this case, Purdue Pharma L. P., filed for bankruptcy after facing a wa=
ve of litigation for its role in the opioid epidemic. Purdue=E2=80=99s long=
-time owners, members of the Sackler family, confronted a growing number of=
 suits too. But instead of declaring bankruptcy, they chose a different pat=
h. From the court overseeing Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy, they sought and w=
on an order extinguishing vast numbers of existing and potential claims aga=
inst them. They obtained all this without securing the consent of those aff=
ected or placing anything approaching their total assets on the table for t=
heir creditors. The question we face is whether the bankruptcy code authori=
zes a court to issue an order like that.
And he concluded it does not:
A bankruptcy court=E2=80=99s powers are not limitless and do not endow it w=
ith the power to extinguish without their consent claims held by nondebtors=
 (here, the opioid victims) against other nondebtors (here, the Sacklers).
This strikes me as straightforward and correct, but again, it=E2=80=99s a 5=
-4 decision. Justice Brett Kavanaugh wrote the dissent, emphasizing the pra=
gmatic value of getting the Sacklers=E2=80=99 money:

Today=E2=80=99s decision is wrong on the law and devastating for more than =
100,000 opioid victims and their families. The Court=E2=80=99s decision rew=
rites the text of the U. S. Bankruptcy Code and restricts the long-establis=
hed authority of=C2=A0bankruptcy courts to fashion fair and equitable relie=
f for mass-tort victims. As a result, opioid victims are now deprived of th=
e substantial monetary recovery that they long fought for and finally secur=
ed after years of litigation. =E2=80=A6
The Bankruptcy Code vests bankruptcy courts with broad discretion to approv=
e =E2=80=9Cappropriate=E2=80=9D plan provisions. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In this mas=
s-tort bankruptcy case, the Bankruptcy Court exercised that discretion appr=
opriately=E2=80=94indeed, admirably. It approved a bankruptcy reorganizatio=
n plan for Purdue Pharma that built up the estate to=C2=A0approximately $7 =
billion by securing a $5.5 to $6 billion settlement payment from the Sackle=
rs, who were officers and directors of Purdue.=C2=A0The plan then guarantee=
d substantial and equitable compensation to Purdue=E2=80=99s many victims a=
nd creditors, including more than 100,000 individual opioid victims. The pl=
an also provided significant funding for thousands of state and local gover=
nments to prevent and treat opioid addiction.
The plan was a shining example of the bankruptcy system at work. Not surpri=
singly, therefore, virtually all of the opioid victims and creditors in thi=
s case fervently support approval of Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy reorganiza=
tion plan. And all 50 state Attorneys General have signed on to the plan=E2=
=80=94a rare consensus. The only relevant exceptions to the nearly universa=
l desire for plan approval are a small group of Canadian creditors and one =
lone individual.
But the Court now throws out the plan=E2=80=94and in doing so, categoricall=
y prohibits non-debtor releases, which have long been a critical tool for b=
ankruptcy courts to manage mass-tort bankruptcies like this one.

Honestly that strikes me as correct too. A bankruptcy court does not have t=
he power to throw out lawsuits against people who are not in bankruptcy, ev=
en though that power really would be useful.

