George Jarkesy Jr. is a fund manager who, according to the US Securities an=
d Exchange Commission, did some frauds. So the SEC sued to stop him and mak=
e him pay fines. But rather than sue him in federal court, the SEC sued him=
 in its own in-house courts.
Why does the SEC have in-house courts? Well, historically, the answer goes =
something like this. The SEC has to make lots of regulatory determinations =
about companies and investment advisers.=C2=A0Investment advisers, for inst=
ance, are typically registered with the SEC. If you do certain bad things, =
you can=E2=80=99t be registered with the SEC, so the SEC sometimes needs to=
 decide if you have done those bad things, so it can revoke your registrati=
on. How does it decide? Well, it has a sort of quasi-judicial process, in w=
hich an SEC employee called an administrative law judge hears both sides of=
 the case (your side, and the SEC enforcement lawyers=E2=80=99 side) and th=
en decides if you did it. And then you can appeal to the bosses of the SEC =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the actual commissioners =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you disagree with=
 the ALJ=E2=80=99s decision. The point is that the SEC,=C2=A0as an institut=
ion, has to make certain decisions, and the in-house courts are a way to ma=
ke those decisions fairly.
But historically the in-house courts could not decide to=C2=A0fine individu=
als, because a decision to impose a fine is not up to the SEC. If the SEC=
=E2=80=99s enforcement lawyers wanted to fine you, they had to sue you in a=
 real court, where a jury would get to decide if you did something wrong. B=
ut in 2010, Congress passed the Dodd-Frank Act, which changed this rule: No=
w the SEC could impose fines using its in-house courts.
An SEC ALJ determined that Jarkesy did the frauds and fined him $300,000. H=
e went to court, arguing that this was unconstitutional: The US Constitutio=
n gives him a right to a jury trial if he is accused of fraud.=C2=A0
We have talked about this case a few times, but honestly we never talked mu=
ch about this claim. It just seemed right to me? My Bloomberg Opinion colle=
ague Noah Feldman agreed with Jarkesy all the way back in 2015 that it was =
unconstitutional for the SEC to impose fines in its in-house courts, and I =
said in 2022 that doing so =E2=80=9Cseems to cause more trouble than it sav=
es.=E2=80=9D The SEC should just sue fraudsters in court! It=E2=80=99s fine=
! They win most of those cases anyway!
Jarkesy won his case at the US Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, and =
the SEC appealed to the Supreme Court. Today, unsurprisingly, he won there =
too: The Supreme Court ruled, by a 6-to-3 vote, that it is unconstitutional=
 for the SEC to fine individuals in its in-house courts. The SEC has to see=
k =E2=80=9Ccivil penalties=E2=80=9D (like fines) in real courts; it can onl=
y use in-house courts to make its own regulatory decisions. =E2=80=9CA defe=
ndant facing a fraud suit has the right to be tried by a jury of his peers =
before a neutral adjudicator,=E2=80=9D wrote Justice Gorsuch for the majori=
ty.=C2=A0
Again, this strikes me as (1) unsurprising and (2) not a big change to the =
SEC=E2=80=99s procedures. But when we have talked about Jarkesy=E2=80=99s c=
ase before, it was about his more sweeping claims. He argued not only that =
he had a constitutional right to a jury trial, but also that Congress had u=
nconstitutionally delegated legislative power to the SEC. The idea is that =
only Congress can make laws, and the decision about whether to bring cases =
in in-house courts or in regular courts is fundamentally a legislative deci=
sion that has to be left to Congress, not the SEC. This struck me as crazy =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0surely the decision about where to sue is an executive decis=
ion? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the appeals court endorsed it. If you take it serio=
usly, I wrote in 2022, that=E2=80=99s a big deal:
The point is that the SEC=E2=80=99s actual legislative actions =E2=80=94 wr=
iting rules about stock buybacks or swaps disclosure or climate change =E2=
=80=94 are now in danger. It used to be accepted as a routine matter that t=
he SEC could make rules under a very broad grant of power from Congress to =
regulate securities markets in the public interest.=C2=A0I am not sure that=
 is true anymore.
I continue to think that there is a live possibility that, in the not too d=
istant future, the Supreme Court will rule that the SEC has no power to mak=
e rules, and all of its rules are invalid. But not today. The court ruled t=
hat Jarkesy had a constitutional right to a jury trial, and stopped there: =
=E2=80=9CWe do not reach the remaining constitutional issues and affirm the=
 ruling of the Fifth Circuit on the Seventh Amendment ground alone.=E2=80=
=9D
In some sense I would count this as a victory for the SEC.=C2=A0Oh, sure, i=
t lost, but it was definitely going to=C2=A0lose. This is a relatively narr=
ow loss: It can=E2=80=99t seek fines in its in-house courts, but its basic =
system of rulemaking survives. For now. Still, Justice Sonia Sotomayor wrot=
e in her dissent: =E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s decision is a massive sea change=
. Litigants seeking further dismantling of the =E2=80=98administrative stat=
e=E2=80=99 have reason to rejoice in their win=C2=A0today, but those of us =
who cherish the rule of law have nothing to celebrate.=E2=80=9D

