<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankruptcy is a very powerful part of US law. =
When a company files for bankruptcy, it=E2=80=99s usually because a lot of =
people have a lot of valid claims against it. It has borrowed a lot of mone=
y, promised to pay it back, and failed to do so; perhaps it has taken money=
 from customers and not delivered the goods; perhaps it has promised its wo=
rkers pensions and reneged on its promises; perhaps it has harmed a lot of =
people and been sued for damages.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of those people have a good moral case to =
get their money, and also they are=C2=A0<em>legally=C2=A0</em>entitled to i=
t. But there is not enough money. And so the company files for bankruptcy, =
and the bankruptcy court has the power to say =E2=80=9Cnope, you don=E2=80=
=99t get the money that you deserve and are legally owed.=E2=80=9D There ar=
e specific rules in the bankruptcy code that determine how the court uses t=
hat power =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally, secured creditors get paid back before =
unsecured ones, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there is also an element of negotia=
tion and compromise among the claimants, and an element of discretion for t=
he bankruptcy judge. The bankruptcy judge=E2=80=99s basic role is to make t=
he fairest possible division of what=E2=80=99s left in a fundamentally unfa=
ir situation.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the judge has a lot of=C2=A0power=C2=A0to =
do that. If the company has, for instance, <em>killed your relatives</em>, =
and you have sued the company in your state=E2=80=99s courts to try to puni=
sh it and get compensation, the bankruptcy judge can=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2F=
jYi51c2NvdXJ0cy5nb3YvZmFxL2xhd3N1aXQtd2hhdC1pZi1vbmUtd2FzLWZpbGVkLWJhbmtydX=
B0Y3ktY2FzZS13YXMtZmlsZWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f0941c7" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>st=
op that lawsuit</em></a>, because once the company is in bankruptcy essenti=
ally all of the claims against it get centralized in bankruptcy. The bankru=
ptcy court decides how to allocate the company=E2=80=99s assets among the c=
laimants, and then all of their claims are extinguished forever.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This power is so broad that bankruptcy judges =
sometimes go overboard.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMjMvdGhlLXB1cmR1ZS1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LWRpZG4tdC13b3J=
rP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBa9ddf2a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked</a> a few <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMzEvcHVyZHVlLXBoYXJtYS1zLWJhbm=
tydXB0Y3ktd29ya3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
W1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249=
bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd4705ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">times</a> about t=
he Purdue Pharma LP bankruptcy. The essential points are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Purdue makes opioid painkillers that =
led to an addiction crisis and killed a lot of people.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Various people =E2=80=94=C2=A0victims, their families,=
 states, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0sued Purdue for its actions.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This has left Purdue facing perhaps trillions of d=
ollars of morally and legally valid obligations to its victims.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Purdue does not have trillions of dollars. It=
s business is worth perhaps a few billion dollars.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">It filed for bankruptcy, and its lawyers, together with la=
wyers for victims and the bankruptcy court, came up with a plan to split up=
 the value of Purdue and give it to the victims.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The victims would not get nearly as much as they would otherwise =
be entitled to =E2=80=94=C2=A0individual victims would get between $3,500 a=
nd $48,000 of compensation, orders of magnitude less than a jury would prob=
ably give them =E2=80=94 but there is only so much money at Purdue.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Purdue=E2=80=99s owners, the Sackler fami=
ly, got very rich over the years from their ownership of Purdue. In particu=
lar, in the years=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>the opioid crisis became widely =
recognized, Purdue paid about $11 billion of dividends and distributions to=
 the Sacklers. They are billionaires, even though the company that they ran=
 has a net worth of, on some assumptions,=C2=A0<em>negative trillions of do=
llars.</em>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This seems pretty unfair to, esse=
ntially, everybody. I mean even to the Sacklers, kind of.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the Sacklers offered to pitch in up to $6 billi=
on of their own money, as part of the bankruptcy plan,=C2=A0to help pay the=
 opioid victims.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In exchange, though, they wanted =
the bankruptcy court to forever extinguish all opioid-related lawsuits=C2=
=A0<em>against them</em>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank=
ruptcy court =E2=80=94=C2=A0and a majority, though not all, of the victims =
=E2=80=94 agreed to the deal.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can analyze that deal on several levels. T=
here is the level of moral fairness: The Sacklers, loosely speaking, extrac=
ted $11 billion for themselves by running a company with a net social value=
 of perhaps negative trillions of dollars. And now they have agreed to give=
 back roughly half of it, leaving them still billionaires. Arguably you sho=
uld become a billionaire by doing stuff with=C2=A0<em>positive=C2=A0</em>va=
lue and keeping some of it for yourself; doing stuff with <em>enormous=C2=
=A0negative value=C2=A0</em>and getting billions for yourself seems bad. As=
 a matter of fairness, the Sacklers should perhaps have to give back, you k=
now, all of it, or almost all of it, or perhaps more than all of it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then there is the pragmatic level.=C2=A0<e=
m>How=C2=A0</em>are you going to get the Sacklers to give up all their mone=
y? You could sue them, sure, of course. The entity that is most obvious lia=
ble for the opioid crisis is=C2=A0<em>Purdue</em>, the company, which is ve=
ry bankrupt, but you can probably find some causes of action to sue the Sac=
klers. For one thing, some Sacklers were executives or board members of Pur=
due, so you could sue them personally for their own actions running Purdue.=
 (But not all of them were.) For another thing, there are arguments under t=
he bankruptcy code that they should not have been able to extract $11 billi=
on from the company while it was facing all this opioid liability, that the=
 dividends they got were =E2=80=9Cfraudulent transfers=E2=80=9D and can be =
clawed back by the company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are problems with all of this. There are=
 a lot of Sacklers. They can hire good lawyers. Some of them live abroad. M=
uch of their money is in trusts that a US court might not be able to get ac=
cess to. If you sued all of them, it would be expensive and time-consuming =
and you might not get much money. You might! And you might at least make li=
fe very unpleasant for them, which has its own virtues.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the majority of the victims, and the bankr=
uptcy court, concluded that getting $6 billion from the Sacklers in the ban=
kruptcy settlement was better than the victims would do by suing them perso=
nally. And so they reached the pragmatic compromise that they=E2=80=99d tak=
e $6 billion, and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>sue for the rest, rather than tryi=
ng to get the whole $11 billion and possibly ending up with nothing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then there is the legal level. The Sackler=
s weren=E2=80=99t willing to pay $6 billion just to get=C2=A0<em>most</em>,=
 or=C2=A0<em>almost all</em>, of the victims to agree not to sue them. Ther=
e are so many victims, so many people who could sue. If they paid the $6 bi=
llion to extinguish 99% of the claims, they would still spend the rest of t=
heir lives fighting lawsuits from the other 1% of the victims.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Sacklers wanted to pay $6 billion to get r=
id of=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the claims against them<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Sackler discharge they propose=
d comprised a release and an injunction. The release sought to void not jus=
t current opioid-related claims against the family, but future ones as well=
. It sought to ban not just claims by creditors participating in the bankru=
ptcy proceeding, but claims by anyone who might otherwise sue Purdue. It so=
ught to extinguish not only claims for negligence, but also claims for frau=
d and willful misconduct. And it proposed to end all these lawsuits without=
 the consent of the opioid victims who brought them. To enforce this releas=
e, the Sacklers sought an injunction =E2=80=9Cforever stay[ing], restrain[i=
ng,] and enjoin[ing]=E2=80=9D claims against them. That injunction would no=
t just prevent suits against the company=E2=80=99s officers and directors b=
ut would run in favor of hundreds, if not thousands, of Sackler family memb=
ers and entities under their control.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They wanted the bankruptcy court to issue an o=
rder saying, in essence, that nobody could sue the Sacklers over opioids ev=
er again.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, again, is a thing that bankruptcy courts=
 do! Almost. Bankruptcy courts=C2=A0<em>are</em>, at their core, in the bus=
iness of issuing orders saying that nobody can sue the bankrupt company eve=
r again. That's what they do; that=E2=80=99s what bankruptcy is. But of cou=
rse=C2=A0<em>the Sacklers aren=E2=80=99t bankrupt</em>. The bankruptcy case=
 is about <em>Purdue</em>, the company, not the Sacklers personally. It=E2=
=80=99s just that, to fairly resolve the Purdue bankruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
o maximize the amount of money Purdue has to distribute to victims, and to =
distribute it fairly =E2=80=94=C2=A0it would help to get the $6 billion fro=
m the Sacklers, and in exchange for that $6 billion they want the same fina=
lity that Purdue gets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, in bankruptcy law, called a =E2=80=9C=
third-party release=E2=80=9D: The idea is that the bankruptcy court extingu=
ishes all the claims, not only against the bankrupt company, but also again=
st some related third parties who are involved with the company. Some bankr=
uptcy courts think that this is allowed, part of the enormous power they ha=
ve to craft fair outcomes and reasonable compromises. Other bankruptcy cour=
ts think that it is not allowed: The bankruptcy code gives them the power t=
o end all lawsuits against=C2=A0<em>the bankrupt company</em>, but that=E2=
=80=99s it. Stopping people who are not in bankruptcy from suing other peop=
le who are not in bankruptcy is a clear overreach.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My impression is that, as a pragmatic matter, =
giving the Sacklers a third-party release was probably a good idea, but tha=
t, as a legal matter, it does seem pretty iffy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, the bankruptcy court gave them the rel=
ease. A federal district court reversed, saying that third-party releases a=
re illegal. Last year, an appeals court <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMzEvcHVyZHVlLXBoYXJtYS1zLWJhbmtydXB0Y3ktd29y=
a3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCdd4705ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">reversed again</a>, allowing th=
e third-party release. And today, on a 5-to-4 vote, the US Supreme Court re=
versed again, finding that third-party releases are not allowed. Justice Ne=
il Gorsuch <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3586144=
9.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yM3BkZi8yMy0xMj=
RfOG5rMC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdde8caa6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote the majority=
 opinion</a>, emphasizing the unfairness of granting the release:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But beneath [the bankruptcy code=
=E2=80=99s] complexity lies a simple bargain: A debtor can win a discharge =
of its debts if it proceeds with honesty and places virtually all its asset=
s on the table for its creditors. The debtor in this case, Purdue Pharma L.=
 P., filed for bankruptcy after facing a wave of litigation for its role in=
 the opioid epidemic. Purdue=E2=80=99s long-time owners, members of the Sac=
kler family, confronted a growing number of suits too. But instead of decla=
ring bankruptcy, they chose a different path. From the court overseeing Pur=
due=E2=80=99s bankruptcy, they sought and won an order extinguishing vast n=
umbers of existing and potential claims against them. They obtained all thi=
s without securing the consent of those affected or placing anything approa=
ching their total assets on the table for their creditors. The question we =
face is whether the bankruptcy code authorizes a court to issue an order li=
ke that.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And he concluded it does not:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bankruptcy court=E2=80=99s power=
s are not limitless and do not endow it with the power to extinguish withou=
t their consent claims held by nondebtors (here, the opioid victims) agains=
t other nondebtors (here, the Sacklers).</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as straightforward and correct=
, but again, it=E2=80=99s a 5-4 decision. Justice Brett Kavanaugh wrote the=
 dissent, emphasizing the pragmatic value of getting the Sacklers=E2=80=99 =
money:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today=E2=80=99s decision is wrong on the law a=
nd devastating for more than 100,000 opioid victims and their families. The=
 Court=E2=80=99s decision rewrites the text of the U. S. Bankruptcy Code an=
d restricts the long-established authority of=C2=A0bankruptcy courts to fas=
hion fair and equitable relief for mass-tort victims. As a result, opioid v=
ictims are now deprived of the substantial monetary recovery that they long=
 fought for and finally secured after years of litigation. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Bankruptcy Code vests bankruptcy courts wi=
th broad discretion to approve =E2=80=9Cappropriate=E2=80=9D plan provision=
s. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In this mass-tort bankruptcy case, the Bankruptcy Court e=
xercised that discretion appropriately=E2=80=94indeed, admirably. It approv=
ed a bankruptcy reorganization plan for Purdue Pharma that built up the est=
ate to=C2=A0approximately $7 billion by securing a $5.5 to $6 billion settl=
ement payment from the Sacklers, who were officers and directors of Purdue.=
=C2=A0The plan then guaranteed substantial and equitable compensation to Pu=
rdue=E2=80=99s many victims and creditors, including more than 100,000 indi=
vidual opioid victims. The plan also provided significant funding for thous=
ands of state and local governments to prevent and treat opioid addiction.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The plan was a shining example of the bankrupt=
cy system at work. Not surprisingly, therefore, virtually all of the opioid=
 victims and creditors in this case fervently support approval of Purdue=E2=
=80=99s bankruptcy reorganization plan. And all 50 state Attorneys General =
have signed on to the plan=E2=80=94a rare consensus. The only relevant exce=
ptions to the nearly universal desire for plan approval are a small group o=
f Canadian creditors and one lone individual.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the Court now throws out the plan=E2=80=94=
and in doing so, categorically prohibits non-debtor releases, which have lo=
ng been a critical tool for bankruptcy courts to manage mass-tort bankruptc=
ies like this one.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Honestly that strikes me as correct too. A ban=
kruptcy court does not have the power to throw out lawsuits against people =
who are not in bankruptcy, even though that power really would be useful.</=
p>
