temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">case</a> a few times, but hon=
estly we never talked much about this claim. It just seemed right to me? My=
 Bloomberg Opinion colleague <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMTUtMTAtMDIvc2VjLXMtbmV3LWNvdXJ0LXBvd2Vycy1hcmVuLXQtZ29pbmctYXdheT9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjI3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA2MjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB946b44ab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Noah Feldman</a> agreed with Jarkesy all =
the way back in 2015 that it was unconstitutional for the SEC to impose fin=
es in its in-house courts, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTkvaXMtdGhlLXNlYy11bmNvbnN0aXR1dGlvbmFsP2NtcGlkPUJCR=
DA2MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy=
JnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cCc9b50304" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">I said in 2022</a> that doing so =E2=80=9Cseems to c=
ause more trouble than it saves.=E2=80=9D The SEC should just sue fraudster=
s in court! It=E2=80=99s fine! They win most of those cases anyway!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jarkesy won his case at the US Court of Appeal=
s for the Fifth Circuit, and the SEC appealed to the Supreme Court. Today, =
unsurprisingly, he won there too: The Supreme Court ruled, by a 6-to-3 vote=
, that it is unconstitutional for the SEC to fine individuals in its in-hou=
se courts. The SEC has to seek =E2=80=9Ccivil penalties=E2=80=9D (like fine=
s) in real courts; it can only use in-house courts to make its own regulato=
ry decisions. =E2=80=9CA defendant facing a fraud suit has the right to be =
tried by a jury of his peers before a neutral adjudicator,=E2=80=9D <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yM3BkZi8yMi04NTlfMTkyNC5wZGY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63c09fc3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote Justice Gorsuch for the majori=
ty</a>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, this strikes me as (1) unsurprising and=
 (2) not a big change to the SEC=E2=80=99s procedures. But when we have tal=
ked about Jarkesy=E2=80=99s case before, it was about his more sweeping cla=
ims. He argued not only that he had a constitutional right to a jury trial,=
 but also that Congress had unconstitutionally delegated legislative power =
to the SEC. The idea is that only Congress can make laws, and the decision =
about whether to bring cases in in-house courts or in regular courts is fun=
damentally a legislative decision that has to be left to Congress, not the =
SEC. This struck me as crazy =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely the decision about where=
 to sue is an executive decision? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the appeals court endo=
rsed it. If you take it seriously, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTkvaXMtdGhlLXNlYy11bmNvbnN0aXR1dGlvbmFsP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDA2MjcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cDc9b50304" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">I wrote in 2022</a>, that=E2=80=99s a big deal:<=
/p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that the SEC=E2=80=99=
s <em>actual </em>legislative actions =E2=80=94 writing rules about stock b=
uybacks or swaps disclosure or climate change =E2=80=94 are now in danger. =
It used to be accepted as a routine matter that the SEC could make rules un=
der a very broad grant of power from Congress to regulate securities market=
s in the public interest.=C2=A0I am not sure that is true anymore.</p></blo=
ckquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I continue to think that there is a live possi=
bility that, in the not too distant future, the Supreme Court will rule tha=
t the SEC has no power to make rules, and all of its rules are invalid. But=
 not today. The court ruled that Jarkesy had a constitutional right to a ju=
ry trial, and stopped there: =E2=80=9CWe do not reach the remaining constit=
utional issues and affirm the ruling of the Fifth Circuit on the Seventh Am=
endment ground alone.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense I would count this as a victory =
for the SEC.=C2=A0Oh, sure, it <em>lost</em>, but it was definitely going t=
o=C2=A0<em>lose</em>. This is a relatively narrow loss: It can=E2=80=99t se=
ek fines in its in-house courts, but its basic system of rulemaking survive=
s. For now. Still, Justice Sonia Sotomayor wrote in her dissent: =E2=80=9CT=
oday=E2=80=99s decision is a massive sea change. Litigants seeking further =
dismantling of the =E2=80=98administrative state=E2=80=99 have reason to re=
joice in their win=C2=A0today, but those of us who cherish the rule of law =
have nothing to celebrate.=E2=80=9D</p>
