<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDYtMjQvYm9vbWVyLWNhbmR5LWJ1c2luZXNzLWlzLWJvb21pbmc_Y21wa=
WQ9QkJEMDYyNzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3Ns=
ZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNjI3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBd8187e1a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote on Monday</a> about a hypothetical, bad=
 financial product:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give me $100 today.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a year, I give you your $100 back, plus any =
return on the S&amp;P 500 stock index, capped at 5% (i.e. you get $105 back=
 if the S&amp;P is up more than 5%) and floored at 0% (i.e. you get $100 ba=
ck if the S&amp;P goes down).</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I intended to make fun of this product; this p=
roduct is a little derivatives structuring joke. The way I=C2=A0<em>hedge=
=C2=A0</em>this product =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way I produce returns that allow=
 me to pay=C2=A0you back the contracted amount =E2=80=94=C2=A0has nothing t=
o do with the S&amp;P 500. I don=E2=80=99t buy any stocks. I just buy a one=
-year Treasury bill, which pays me about 5.1% for the year. Then, if stocks=
 are up, I pay you the stock return, up to 5%. And I keep the extra 0.1%.=
=C2=A0If stocks are flat or down, I keep the whole 5.1%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDYtMjYvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtaXMtZ2V0dGluZ=
y1tb3JlLWV0ZnMtdGhhdC1vZmZlci0xMDAtZG93bnNpZGUtcHJvdGVjdGlvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQw=
NjI3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ=
1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA2MjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB7da2a180" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Emily Graffeo reports</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A new ETF is promising a ... place to ride it =
out for the next six months, with none of the losses if the stock market sw=
oons.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Innovator Equity Defined Protection ETF - =
6 Mo Jan/July (ticker=C2=A0JAJL) will be the shortest-term 100% buffer fund=
, an expanding universe of those that use options to deliver some of the st=
ock market=E2=80=99s gains while promising protection against the downside.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over a six-month holding period that begins on=
 the fund=E2=80=99s first trading day on July 1, JAJL will match the price =
return of the SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF trust up to a cap of roughly 4.8%. Inves=
tors will need to hold the fund for the entire period to receive the full r=
isk protection. At the end of the year, they can redeem their shares or rol=
l them into the next cycle.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hmm: Stock returns with a floor of 0% and a ca=
p of 4.8%. Sorry Inovator!=C2=A0But, no, I=E2=80=99m kidding. My product is=
 bad; Innovator=E2=80=99s product is fine. The trick is that my product off=
ers the S&amp;P return up to a cap of 5%=C2=A0<em>for the year</em>, which =
is what you=E2=80=99d get on T-bills. Innovator=E2=80=99s offers the S&amp;=
P return up to a cap of 4.8%=C2=A0<em>for six months</em>. And then, after =
the six months, it does it again (with a new cap).<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If you hold it for a year and the S&amp;P goes up 30%, you probab=
ly get a return of like 9% or so, which is much better than my dumb hypothe=
tical.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is fine. Conceptually the way you do this=
 is something like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give them $100 today.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They spend about $97.40 to buy a Treasury bil=
l that will mature in six months at $100.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They use the remaining $2.60 to b=
uy a six-month call spread on the S&amp;P 500.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That is, they buy a six-month call option on the S&amp;P, struck =
at today=E2=80=99s price, and sell a six-month call option on the S&amp;P, =
struck at 104.8% of today=E2=80=99s price. This gives them the return on th=
e S&amp;P index above today=E2=80=99s price, but capped at 4.8%.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s economically what=E2=80=99s hap=
pening, but the actual mechanics are a bit different: They do all of it thr=
ough <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35861449.2602=
84/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2JvZS5jb20vdHJhZGFibGVfcHJvZHVjdHMvZXF1aXR5X2luZGljZXMv=
ZmxleF9vcHRpb25z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30cb7d9f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Flex options</a=
>, essentially buying the entire return profile through equity options rath=
er than Treasury bills plus equity options.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s an important point too. When I =
made fun of my bad hypothetical product on Monday, I said: =E2=80=9CYou sho=
uld not buy it; you should just buy the Treasury bill yourself instead.=E2=
=80=9D But several readers emailed to disagree. Their point was: If you buy=
 a Treasury bill, you get 5.1% interest, but you pay taxes on that interest=
 at ordinary income rates. If you buy my dumb product, you get a return of =
between 0% and 5%, but that return is (probably) in the form of capital gai=
ns.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If my product runs for a year and a day, it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>lo=
ng-term=C2=A0</em>capital gains, which are taxed at a lower rate than ordin=
ary income, so my 5% return=C2=A0cap is worth=C2=A0<em>more</em>, to you, a=
s a taxpayer, than a 5.1% return on T-bills.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even better, if my product runs for=C2=A0<em>l=
onger=C2=A0</em>than that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, say, instead of giving you bac=
k the $105 in a year, I roll it over into a new bet for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
then you (probably) don=E2=80=99t pay the capital gains taxes until you sel=
l out of my product. If you keep this bet on for 20 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0ea=
ch year, I give you the return on the S&amp;P 500, floored at 0% and capped=
 at 5% (or whatever the T-bill rate is that year) =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you d=
on=E2=80=99t pay the taxes until the end of the 20 years. And then, when yo=
u do, you pay capital gains rates.=C2=A0Graffeo writes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elevated interest rates =E2=80=93 =
particularly at the short end of the Treasury curve =E2=80=93- are helping =
ETF issuers generate the income needed to offer these kind of funds. While =
that also means investors can get high risk-free payouts on Treasury bills,=
 Bond said the ETF can still provide bigger returns over the six-month peri=
od, particularly when the tax advantages are factored in.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that this is part of the point of thes=
e buffer funds. The proposition they offer is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t take equity risk: I=
f you put in $100, you always get back at least $100.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">You get some return that is sort of centered around the=
 risk-free rate: You might get a bit more than 5% per year (if stocks are u=
p), or you might get a bit less or even zero, but you=E2=80=99re not going =
to lose money and you=E2=80=99re not going to make 30%.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">That return is=C2=A0<em>taxed=C2=A0</em>more favorabl=
y than just investing in Treasury bills. Instead of earning interest on Tre=
asuries, you are taxed like you hold stocks for the long term.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice how magical this is. I wrote down, abov=
e, how you=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>structure this product (not how it is a=
ctually structured): You buy a Treasury bill and some stock options. The Tr=
easury bill accounts for roughly=C2=A0<em>97%=C2=A0</em>of the value of the=
 product; the stock options account for a bit less than 3%. But the returns=
 on the product are taxed like stock returns, not Treasury bill interest. T=
hat=E2=80=99s good financial engineering!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/35861449.260284/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjIvcHV0LXRoZS1tb25leS1pbi10aGUtYm94eD9jbXBpZD1CQkQw=
NjI3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ=
1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA2MjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBac63e9d7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">talked earlier this year</a> about another exchange-tr=
aded fund, called BOXX (or more formally Alpha Architect 1-3 Month Box ETF)=
, which also used a collection of stock options to achieve relatively risk-=
free returns. The explicit proposition of BOXX is that you get paid the Tre=
asury bill rate, but it is taxed as long-term capital gains, and you pay ta=
