ork: Tax rules prevent you from, in essence, transforming interest income i=
nto capital gains by buying and selling identical stock options.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But buffer funds are probably fine? (Not tax a=
dvice!) Buffer funds=C2=A0buy and sell=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0</em>stock o=
ptions, different enough that your return is not the T-bill rate but someth=
ing a bit riskier, a bit more linked to stock returns. Not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=
=A0</em>much more linked to stock returns =E2=80=94=C2=A0your return here i=
s between 0% and 4.8%, when T-bills would return about 2.7%<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
